    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-09-06T14:37:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-09-06T14:37:00-05:00" n="201"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d201">
                <head>201. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Lebanon</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d201fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, AV 12 <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">US</gloss>. Unclassified; Flash. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_STW1">Seelye</persName> and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_DRP1">Davies</persName>. It was repeated Immediate to Amman,
                            <gloss target="#t_USINT1">USINT</gloss> Cairo, Brussels, London, Paris,
                        and Rome.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-09-06T19:37:00+00:00">September 6, 1970,
                        1937Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>146343. Subject: Hijacking.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Pan Am informs us that Lebanese are refusing to allow Pan Am aircraft to
                        land at Beirut Airport. We consider it extremely important that permission
                        for such landing be granted. Embassy instructed to do everything possible to
                        persuade Lebanese Government to allow aircraft to land.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>We have just seen ticker item quoting Amman “airport sources” to effect
                        that airports at Amman, Damascus and Baghdad have refused <pb facs="0636"
                            n="603" xml:id="pg_603"/> landing permission to two aircraft. Aside from
                        political desirability plane and passengers land at Beirut, safety of planes
                        and passengers is jeopardized by continued inability aircraft find place to
                        land.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
